file-name: XC583157-Blue-throated Bee-eater-calls-4-Xeno-combined-Kledang-Sayong Forest Reserve, Ipoh, Perak, Malaysia-17th August 2020.mp3
rmk: I was watching a pair of adult Blue-throated Bee-eater doing aerial sallies to catch insects at the forest fringe. Calls are given both while perched and in the air. There is considerable variation in how calls are used and mixed. The commonest call is a fast call given singly or in a run of 2-4 notes. Wells (1999) describes it as ‘terrip-terrip’. The other call in the recording is much softer and extended (5-10 notes). Wells (1999) describes it as ‘trrurrip’. The sonograms show that these two calls are very distinctly different. The first call is a contact call while the second is more communicative, almost a ‘begging or pleading-like’ quality.
